### Notable Personnel

The annals of Chicago Maroons football are graced by individuals whose contributions have left an indelible mark on the sport. Many have been recognized for their exceptional talent and impact.

#### College Football Hall of Fame

*   **[Jay Berwanger](/Jay_Berwanger)** (Halfback, 1933–1935): Inducted in 1954, Berwanger achieved unparalleled recognition as the first-ever recipient of the [Heisman Trophy](/Heisman_Trophy). His collegiate career was a showcase of skill and leadership.
*   **[Hugo Bezdek](/Hugo_Bezdek)** (Fullback, 1905): Inducted in 1954, Bezdek's collegiate playing career at Chicago was a prelude to his highly successful coaching tenures at Oregon, Arkansas, and Penn State.
*   **[Fritz Crisler](/Fritz_Crisler)** (End, 1919–1921): Inducted in 1954, Crisler's time as a player at Chicago was followed by distinguished coaching careers at Minnesota, Princeton, and Michigan, where he significantly influenced the game.
*   **[Paul Des Jardien](/Paul_Des_Jardien)** (Center, 1912–1914): Inducted in 1955, Des Jardien was a standout player, earning All-American honors in both 1913 and 1914, contributing to the Maroons' championship aspirations.
*   **[Walter Eckersall](/Walter_Eckersall)** (Quarterback, 1903–1906): Inducted in 1951, Eckersall was the brilliant field general of the 1905 national championship team, renowned for his exceptional playmaking abilities.
*   **[Clarence Herschberger](/Clarence_Herschberger)** (Fullback, 1895–1898): Inducted in 1970, Herschberger holds the distinction of being the first player from the Western region selected as a first-team All-American, a testament to his groundbreaking talent.
*   **[Tiny Maxwell](/Tiny_Maxwell)** (Guard, 1902, 1904–1905): Inducted in 1974, Maxwell was a pivotal member of the 1905 national championship team, earning All-American honors for his crucial role.
*   **[Clark Shaughnessy](/Clark_Shaughnessy)** (Coach, 1933–1939): Inducted in 1968, Shaughnessy's coaching career spanned five decades, and his tenure at Chicago, though marked by challenges, was a significant chapter in his distinguished path.
*   **[Amos Alonzo Stagg](/Amos_Alonzo_Stagg)** (Coach, 1892–1932): Inducted in 1951, Stagg is rightly hailed as "The Grand Old Man of the Midway." His legendary coaching career at the University of Chicago fundamentally shaped the sport of football.
*   **[Walter Steffen](/Walter_Steffen)** (Quarterback, 1906–1908): Inducted in 1969, Steffen was a prolific scorer, amassing 156 points during a period where his teams achieved a remarkable 13–2–1 record. He was a first-team All-American in 1908.
*   **[Andy "Polyphemus" Wyant](/Andy_Wyant)** (Guard, Center, 1892–1894): Inducted in 1962, Wyant had an extensive playing career, competing for eight varsity seasons across Bucknell and Chicago, demonstrating remarkable longevity and skill.

#### Other Notable Figures

*   **[Walter S. Kennedy]**: A skilled quarterback who played for Stagg's teams during the 1898–1899 seasons.
*   **[Wally Marks]**: A versatile fullback and halfback from 1924–1926, who was a key leader on Chicago's last Big Ten championship team.
*   **[Nelson Norgren]**: A distinguished athlete who played football under Stagg and later coached the Chicago basketball team for an impressive span from 1921–1942 and again from 1944–1957.
*   **[Laurens Shull]**: An All-American player whose promising career was tragically cut short when he was killed in action during [World War I](/World_War_I).
*   **[Frederick A. Speik]**: An exceptional end who earned All-American honors in 1904, showcasing his talent during a significant period of the program's history.
*   **[Herman Stegeman]**: A player on the 1913 national championship team, Stegeman went on to a notable coaching career, leading football, baseball, basketball, and track programs at the University of Georgia.
*   **[John Webster Thomas]**: An All-American fullback in 1922, Thomas played under Stagg from 1921–1923, contributing significantly to the team's success.
*   **[Mysterious Walker]**: A talented player for Stagg from 1904–1906, Walker later embarked on a lengthy coaching career at the collegiate level from 1907–1940.
*   **[Graham Kernwein]**: A player for Stagg from 1923–1925, Kernwein later continued his football career professionally, playing in the NFL.

